---
import architectureSvg from "../../assets/diagrams/skynet-architecture.svg?raw";
import frameTransportSvg from "../../assets/diagrams/skynet-frame-transport.svg?raw";
import MermaidDiagram from "../../components/MermaidDiagram.astro";
import ProjectCTA from "../../components/ProjectCTA.astro";
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
	title="Skynet"
	description="Skynet is Rebecca Clair's from-scratch reimplementation of the architecture behind OpenAI's Atlas browser: a C++23/Qt shell, an out-of-process CEF runtime service, zero-copy GPU frame transport on Linux, and an authenticated CDP gateway for AI agents."
>
	<main class="project-page">
		<a class="back-link" href="/projects/">← Projects</a>
		<article class="content project-detail">
			<p class="eyebrow">Browser engineering · GPU systems · AI-agent infrastructure</p>
			<h1>Skynet</h1>
			<p class="lede">
				Skynet is a from-scratch reimplementation of the architecture behind
				OpenAI's Atlas browser: a native C++23/Qt Quick shell, a separate
				runtime service that owns all Chromium state, zero-copy GPU frame
				transport, and an authenticated control surface that lets AI agents
				drive the browser — the same runtime that also backs a patched Codex
				Desktop as a second embedder.
			</p>

			<h2>The problem</h2>
			<p>
				An AI-powered browser is really two problems wearing one trench coat.
				The first is architectural: if agents, embedders, and the browser
				engine all live in one process, every crash, upgrade, and security
				decision is entangled. Atlas solves this by splitting the app from a
				browser runtime service, but that runtime is proprietary and
				macOS-shaped. The second is brutally practical: getting
				Chromium-rendered frames onto the screen without copying them through
				the CPU, on Linux, across Intel and NVIDIA — the part with the
				reputation for being impossible.
			</p>

			<h2>What I built</h2>
			<ul>
				<li>
					A two-process design: a Qt 6 Quick shell that owns no browser state,
					and a <code>skynet-runtime</code> sidecar that owns every CEF
					browser, client, and off-screen rendering surface.
				</li>
				<li>
					An OWL-compatible, versioned JSON-RPC 2.0 protocol between them —
					profiles, sessions, pages, surfaces, and input — carried over stdio,
					Unix sockets, or loopback WebSocket, derived by reverse engineering
					the real Atlas application bundle.
				</li>
				<li>
					A zero-copy GPU frame lane: CEF renders off-screen in the sidecar
					and frames cross the process boundary as DRM dma-buf file
					descriptors with plane, stride, and modifier metadata, fenced with
					native sync and presented directly in Qt's Vulkan scene graph.
				</li>
				<li>
					An authenticated Chrome DevTools Protocol gateway for agents, with
					bearer tokens and an epoch-based replay guard, so a driver like
					Codex Desktop can control pages without ever touching raw CEF
					internals.
				</li>
				<li>
					Crash-resilient surfaces: the frame stream survives GPU-process and
					renderer crashes in the sidecar and re-establishes itself instead of
					leaving the shell staring at a dead texture.
				</li>
				<li>
					A second embedder, running today: the same runtime embedded into a
					patched Codex Desktop, handing the Electron app real GPU frames over
					a dma-buf file-descriptor-passing socket and taking input back — one
					runtime backing both the Qt shell and an Electron app.
				</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>How it works</h2>
			<p>
				One rule holds everything up: the UI process owns no browser objects —
				not one. The shell renders chrome and forwards intent; the runtime host
				owns CEF, off-screen rendering, page lifecycle, and input injection.
				That boundary is what makes the rest possible: the runtime can crash,
				restart, or be swapped without taking the shell down, and any embedder
				that speaks the protocol gets a browser.
			</p>
			<p>
				The protocol itself came out of research, not guesswork. I extracted
				the actual Atlas application bundle and derived its object model —
				sessions, profiles, web views, layer hosts — from the binaries, then
				reimplemented that shape as an authenticated, versioned JSON-RPC
				surface. Skynet contains none of Atlas's code; it speaks the
				architecture, not the implementation.
			</p>

			<MermaidDiagram
				title="Architecture"
				caption="The shell and the agent are both just clients: every browser object lives in the runtime sidecar, and frames flow back over the zero-copy lane."
				svg={architectureSvg}
			/>

			<p>
				The frame transport is where the GPU work lives. On Linux the
				production default is the <code>gpu-dmabuf</code> lane on both Intel
				and NVIDIA: frames leave CEF as dma-buf descriptors and are imported
				straight into Qt's Vulkan scene graph, never touching the CPU. That
				default exists because of validation, not optimism — GLX dma-buf
				imports sampled black on NVIDIA PRIME under X11, so the policy requires
				Vulkan there and refuses the broken OpenGL path with a clear error
				rather than shipping black surfaces. A shared-memory BGRA lane exists
				as a deliberate, policy-selected fallback, not a silent one.
			</p>

			<MermaidDiagram
				title="Frame transport"
				caption="One frame contract, three lanes: zero-copy dma-buf as the default, shared memory as an explicit policy fallback, and structured-clone frames for Electron embedders."
				svg={frameTransportSvg}
			/>

			<h2>How it achieves the goal</h2>
			<p>
				The goal is a browser runtime that AI can drive and any app can embed,
				without trusting either one with the engine's internals. The CDP
				gateway gives agents real DevTools-grade control, but every exposed
				target maps to a runtime page identifier, every mutating call must
				present the current runtime epoch, and native CEF DevTools stays
				walled off as a development-only oracle. The agent gets capability;
				the runtime keeps custody.
			</p>
			<p>
				It already does the thing it exists to do: a single live surface
				navigates, the GPU zero-copy path works on both Intel and NVIDIA under
				Linux with no CPU copy in the frame path, and the runtime is embedded
				and running inside my daily-driver Codex Desktop. The limits are real
				and worth stating plainly — tabs are still metadata over that one
				surface, extensions are a declared seam rather than a runtime, and the
				OWL parity flags stay off until their conformance suites pass. The
				foundations came first on purpose: process isolation, an authenticated
				protocol, crash recovery, and cross-vendor zero-copy GPU presentation on
				Linux — the part that is not hard so much as unforgiving.
			</p>

			<ProjectCTA />
		</article>
	</main>
</Layout>

<style lang="scss">
	.project-page {
		max-width: 980px;
	}

	.back-link {
		display: inline-block;
		margin-bottom: 1rem;
		color: rgb(var(--accent));
	}

	.project-detail {
		padding-bottom: 2rem;
	}

	.eyebrow {
		margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
		color: var(--grey-mid);
		text-transform: uppercase;
		letter-spacing: 0.08em;
		font-size: 0.85rem;
	}

	h1 {
		font-size: 2.4rem;
		margin-top: 0;
	}

	.lede {
		font-size: 1.2rem;
		color: var(--color-fg-copy);
	}
</style>
